                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18160110-57-off322 t18160110-57-crimeloc324"></join>. On Saturday the 16th of December, I had a shawl and apron hanging in the yard of the house where I live; I saw them between six and seven in the evening; the door is generally left open.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18160110-57-person546">
                  ROBERT 
                  HOUTON
               <interp inst="t18160110-57-person546" type="surname" value="HOUTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160110-57-person546" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160110-57-person546" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in this house; I was going to my labour, and found the prisoner in the passage; she was a stranger, and I asked her where she had been, she said she had been backwards. In consequence of information which the landlady gave me, I followed her, and brought her back, and took the shawl and apron from her. I took her to Worshop-street, where she was committed.</p>
               <p>(Property produced, and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I did not steal them, but found them in the yard; I asked the people in the house who had lost them, and the woman's mother said, my poor woman go about your business; but the man kept me.</p>
               <p>
